column1: the former google software engineer felt a #mix of emotions as she watched the massive walkouts protesting sexual harassment at the corporationâ€™s offices across the globe on thursday. she said it was moving to see thousands of employees demonstrate
column2: but that it was hard not to feel #frustrated and stuck on a nagging question: what took so long?

column1: she also wondered if google would ever say #sorry.
ellis first spoke publicly about experiencing sexual harassment at google in 2015. last week
column2: #google came under global scrutiny after the a new york times investigation revealed that the corporation gave $90m to a top executive after determining that sexual misconduct allegations against him were credible.
it was also long before an uber #scandal sparked a mainstream debate about discrimination in silicon valley
column3: and before the #metoo movement exposed rampant sexual #abuse in many industries.

column2: who is taking google to court on allegations that the company systematically underpays women
column3: spoke to the guardian thursday about this weekâ€™s unprecedented global protests and how she hoped to #spark reforms through her class-action #litigation.";;en;#apology.

column1: this just ends horribly. thank god judges is over. both having these types of judges and my reading of this book. egad!
this story starts out with a levite and a woman--neither are named. if i had to guess
column2: it is allegory about israel returning to god. but the story is horrible. the woman is the second wife of levi. she left him and returned to her home. the hubs goes to get her and spends 5 days drinking and eating (hence the table imagery). then takes his wife and travels towards home. the levite's servant wants to overnight in jebus (jerusalem) but the levite says no. they go to gibeah.

they look for hospitality in a presumably safe town. they receive none until an elderly man comes and takes them in. then the dudes rise up to take the levite priest ""and know him."" but this is not about homosexuality which is consensual sex but about rape which is not consensual. rape is never okay. in this context
column3: raping another man was not a sex act
column4: it was an attack on male honor.

column2: this story begins to be a mirror of the story of lot at sodom & gomorrah (gen. 19). even unto offering two women (the 2nd wife and a daughter). the twist is that rather than running away with god's intervention as lot and family does
column3: the priest throws his wife out the door as a sacrifice to the men. in the morning
column4: she has crawled back to the house and lies near death on the doorstep. the levite goes outside
column6: and ""orders her to get up."" such compassion. she dies before they get home.

column2: the levitical priest cuts his wife into 12 pieces and sends the pieces to all of israel (i.e. 12 tribes
column4: israel is cut up and in pieces--not united--remember

column1: first off fear is a big factor in todayâ€™s post.  as a young teenager when i was sexually abused by my boss he instilled fear beyond belief that it took me 30 years to tell my story.  my whole teenage and adult life revolved around fear and lack of trust.  the first person i learnt to trust was my husband.  the fear that people were talking about me behind my back
column2: the fear that i was constantly being judged by others continuously
column4: i had no voice.  so much that i had these unrealistic expectations of myself because in my eyes i needed to be perfect.  so when i looked at myself and didnâ€™t see perfection it was constantly a way to beat myself up.  so this weeks session really opened my eyes to my patterns of negative self talk.  we get into the studio i undress and was much more comfortable being naked and having someone look at me.  each picture we took i was disgusted with myself.  i literally said nope take another one
column5: nope take another one several times not liking any of them.  i was looking for perfection.  then dani said
column6: nicole i have an idea letâ€™s get you into the silks because that always seems to change your mood and direction of thoughts.  low and behold i get into the silk and like magic she showed me the picture and i couldnâ€™t believe it was me.  dani told me not to get rid of the other pictures and to sit with them and pick something i liked out of each one.  after repeatedly looking at the pictures i began to see something else
column7: i began to accept and see my own beauty for what it was.  i talked about my cellulite and how challenged i am with this weeks photos because they are much more revealing.  i learned through talking with other women that most women when they squeeze their butt cheeks have dimples
column8: this is normal and okay.  i was so reluctant on posting a few of these photos because of my imperfections which was all the more reason why i needed to post all of them this week.  because i didnâ€™t want too!  doing the opposite allows you to move forward into acceptance. iâ€™m breaking free and loving every minute of it! #twosoulsyoga #sudburyyoga #metoo #nudeart #nu";en;#Repost

column1: fuller was an influential early feminist whose writings had a profound impact on later women suffrage campaigners
â€œshe possessed more influence on the thought of american women than any woman previous to her time.â€ olympe de gouges (1755-1793) was a french writer
column2: revolutionary and feminist. born marie gouze in southern france
column3: de gouges was the daughter of a semi-literate butcher. noted for her beauty
column4: at the age of 16 de gouges was forced into an arranged marriage with a much older man. she loathed this situation but escaped from it a year later when her husband died. in 1770 she moved to paris and indulged her passions for writing and political discussion
column5: attending several notable salons and mixing with the likes of jacques brissot and marquis condorcet. de gougesâ€™ politics were moderate
column6: reformist and feminist: she supported a constitutional monarchy rather than a republic; she wanted no harm to come to the king; and
column8: she sought improvements in the rights and conditions of women. she is best known for a political pamphlet titled declaration of the rights of woman

fuck everyone and they're ignorant prejudice to the loved ones left over after a suicide. fuck minorities with a chip on their shoulder about white privledge when it doesn't exist.

column1: 263388;instagram;2018-11-02 07:47:00;FALSE;"âœ last evening i read a story about a girl in an office halloween party at mumbai that got molested. she said she was sloshed and her colleague felt her up and grabbed her and kissed her without consent. she woke up a brief second due the pain of him biting her lip which had left a scar btw
column2: but was too dead to disengage or resist. witnesses to this event on inquiry later said
column3: they thought they two were a couple and didn't recognize she was actually unconcious.

column1: like some of you might be thinking it was the girl's fault to a large extent to have gotten drunk in a public setting that she had to be carried home and has no rememberance of the events of last night. she was negligent
column2: irresponsible and reckless. she should have known men are evil and  should have been careful. right? wrong.
let's switch the gender of the girl to a boy and tell me how you feel about this incident now. is it acceptable? that uncomfortable
column3: beginning to grasp my point feeling you are having right now is the real problem. not the girl who drank too much coz we all know for every 1 drunk girl there are 10 men that get drunk. but the sexual violence against women is 100:1 figuratively. so the problem is not with women or her clothes or her way of life. it is with men that do not recognize women to be humans but objects or opportunities for pleasure. women and men are equal damn it. they may operate and behave differently but  have the same rights and need to be treated with the same kind of respect because for the nth time

after a while we ventured out to explore our surroundings not knowing we'd become stained by others. perhaps our families
column2: perhaps our friends and even our forefathers. we took the blows and carried on with our scars until we began feeling unrecognizable. at that point we turned around desperate to find our way back
column4: to each other andto a time when we never felt seperate from anything or anyone. .

column3: finding each other. loving each other and doing our best to be our amazing

column1: 263831;instagram;2018-11-01 23:03:21;FALSE;"please understand you are not alone. i was a victim of sexual assault. what happened was not your fault
column2: you did nothing wrong. i was young when this happened and again at 13. there are days where it affects me more than most. there are nights where i wake up in cold sweats due to the nightmares what happened still haunts me but i'm no longer ashamed. if you need someone to talk to about your story or if your struggling with gaining yourself back or even nobody knows and your suffering in silence. you are not alone i am here and i will comfort you and talk to you and give you advice or even be the listening ear or the shoulder to cry on. i will not desert you i will be here. my dms are always open. anytime 24/7. the sexual assault hotline is 1-800-656-4673 if you don't feel comfortable with talking to me or friends. i'm not ashamed of what happened and i encourage you to share your story. i love you and will always be here.

column1: this is hard for me. personal post ahead.

column3: and it became a very big secret i buried for about a decade. i didn't want anyone to find out. i felt guilty
column4: and i felt ashamed. i felt disgusted
column5: with myself. i didn't know how to handle it
column6: so i just didn't. i bottled it up deep inside
column7: so that i could keep it contained and it wouldn't affect me. but

column2: i was probably like most other teenagers; moody
column4: apathetic at times. happy go lucky but jaded at the same time. on the inside
column5: i was constantly struggling with inner turmoil.

column1: when i was faced with new conflicts
column2: i would revert back to that safety mechanism of disassociating
column3: and i would hide from it or put it off as long as possible. i was always afraid to go to see doctors because i thought they would find out my secret
column4: so i would avoid them at all costs and be extremely nervous or upset when i did have to go.

column1: i didn't value my body. my first lesson in intimacy told me that my body was for someone else to use and that the rest of me didn't matter. i struggled with depression all through college
column2: and a lot of social interactions would make me uncomfortable or even nauseous.

column1: if i was intimate with someone who i actually cared for
column2: i couldn't focus. i would have flashbacks
column3: and i would get very upset and feel the same shame i had before. one of my biggest struggles in life was learning how to actually feel comfortable and empowered in my body and to enjoy sex.
i still struggle with facing conflict
column5: i struggle with taking care of myself
column6: i struggle with going to see doctors
column8: i struggle to see my worth
column9: i struggle to value my body beyond my looks.

column1: i get these glimpses of myself where i can do anything
column2: and i can see a path for my life to be more meaningful. where i feel at home in my body because i'm focusing on my strength and what i can do and not just how i look. where i feel excited to meet and talk with people. where i'm happy.

column6: so i just didn't. i bottled it up deep inside
column7: so that i could keep it contained and it would not affect me. but

column2: i was probably like most other teenagers; moody

column5: i was constantly struggling with inner turmoil.

column1: when i was faced with new conflicts
column2: i would revert back to that safety mechanism of disassociating
column3: and i would hide from it or put it off as long as possible. i was always afraid to go to see doctors because i thought they would find out my secret
column4: so i would avoid them at all costs and be extremely nervous or upset when i did have to go.

column2: and a lot of social interactions would make me uncomfortable or even nauseous.

column2: i couldn't focus. i would have flashbacks
